### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

Angular Router

### Description

I am trying to easily extract a `:groupId` from my activatedRoute. The url could be `http://apollo-native-tv:4205/admin/groups/ef01886a-167c-4b57-82ed-000f805a73e0/photos 
`.
When I use ActivatedRoute on the `photo` component, I have to traverse 4 or 5 levels down into nested router-outlets to find my `:groupId`.


### Proposed solution

Add a function that returns a merged params map from the whole URL trees root to the current activated outlet so I dont have to traverse the tree finding the param.
```
private getLeafRoute(): ActivatedRouteSnapshot {
  let route = this.activeRouted.root;
  while (route.firstChild) {
    route = route.firstChild;
  }
  return route.snapshot;
}

// Usage
const groupId = this.getLeafRoute().params['groupId'];
```

The `router.currentNavigation()` signal is something that  could possible adds a merged map of all Params from tree up to the leaf?

### Alternatives considered

I could subscribe to Router Events and get the `:groupId` but I find that Router events emits a lot of noisy and I am not sure if that is causing more overhead. I prefer to limit subscriber, I guess.

```
groupId$ = this.router.events.pipe(
  filter(event => event instanceof NavigationEnd),
  map(() => {
    let route = this.router.routerState.root;
    while (route.firstChild) {
      route = route.firstChild;
    }
    return route.snapshot.params['groupId'];
  }),
  filter(Boolean)
);

```

### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

core


### Description

When using a signal that must keep the same reference (e.g. for PrimeNG’s <date-picker> with [ngModel]), the equal function does not behave as expected.

In this case, the underlying array reference must not change for PrimeNG’s binding to work properly. However, when mutating the contents of that array and trying to rely on equal to control when dependents update, the equality check doesn’t work — because the internal signal value is also mutated.

```javascript
<date-picker
    [ngModel]="rangeDates()" // this needs to stay the same reference in order to work (primeNG)
    (ngModelChange)="dateRangeChanged($event)">
</date-picker>

/**
 * value of the date range picker
 * NEEDS to be the same reference in order for the date picker to work correctly
 * otherwise only the first date can be selected
 */
rangeDates = signal<Date[]>([dayjs().startOf('day').toDate(), dayjs().toDate()], {
    equal: (a, b) => {
		    // THE PROBLEM:
		    // this isEqual does not really work because the underlaying signal value got updated aswell when I updated the array
				// therefore the isEqual does not make sence
        return isEqual(
            a.map((date) => (date ? dayjs(date).toISOString() : null)),
            b.map((date) => (date ? dayjs(date).toISOString() : null)),
        );
    },
});

startDateString = computed(() => this.rangeDates()?.[0]?.toISOString());
endDateString = computed(() => this.rangeDates()?.[1]?.toISOString() ?? dayjs().toISOString());

loadHistoryParams = computed(
    () => {
        const deviceId = this.deviceStore.selectedDeviceId();
        const startDateString = this.startDateString();
        const endDateString = this.endDateString();
        return { id: deviceId, startDate: startDateString, endDate: endDateString };
    },
    { equal: isEqual },
);

// load some call
constructor() {
    // updating array, keeping the same ref
    const arr = this.rangeDates();
    arr.length = 0; // clear array
    arr.push(dates[0], dates[1]);
    this.rangeDates.set(arr);

    effect(() => {
        const params = this.loadHistoryParams();
        untracked(() => {
            this.deviceStore.loadConnectionHistoryData(params);
        });
    });
}
```

<img width="1850" height="192" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/5ac61ab0-98f0-4102-8ce3-78a7550a02ad" />

• PrimeNG requires the same array reference for ngModel to function correctly (otherwise only the first date can be selected).
• The equal function seems redundant because when the array is mutated in place, both a and b refer to the same underlying object, making comparison meaningless.

**Other solutions that I could work with:**
1.	Use a second signal just to notify dependents when the array content changes.
(Feels redundant but works.)
2.	Return false in the equal function to always notify dependents.
(Works fine for this case but defeats the purpose of equal.)

**Question / Feature Request**
	•	Should signal() support deep equality for mutable references (like arrays or objects)?


### Please provide the environment you discovered this bug in (run `ng version`)

```true
Angular: 19.2.0
```
